{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630572"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17319"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17319"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.52,0,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69873"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17319"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55329"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10044"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23457"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69873"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBacterial fermentation in the human colon plays an important role in nutrition and gut health.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main products of bacterial fermentation in the human colon?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bile acids","Long-chain fatty acids","Short-chain fatty acids","Amino acids","Simple sugars"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBacterial fermentation is the anaerobic metabolic process where bacteria break down complex carbohydrates. The main products of bacterial fermentation in the colon are \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort-chain fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E, primarily acetate, propionate, and butyrate. These are produced when colonic bacteria ferment dietary fibre and resistant starch that was not digested in the small intestine. Short-chain fatty acids provide energy for colonocytes and can be absorbed into the bloodstream, contributing up to 10% of daily caloric requirements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-chain fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E are absorbed in the small intestine and are not produced by colonic bacteria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple sugars\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily absorbed in the small intestine and are substrates for, rather than products of, bacterial fermentation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmino acids\u003C/strong\u003E are mainly absorbed in the small intestine and are not significant products of colonic bacterial metabolism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBile acids\u003C/strong\u003E are produced by the liver and modified by bacteria but are not products of bacterial fermentation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe production of short-chain fatty acids helps maintain a healthy colonic environment by lowering pH and providing nutrition for the intestinal epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bacterial fermentation is the anaerobic breakdown of carbohydrates by gut bacteria to produce energy.","Short-chain fatty acids produced by colonic bacteria provide up to 10% of human daily caloric requirements.","The main products of bacterial fermentation in the colon are acetate, propionate, and butyrate.","Colonic bacteria primarily ferment dietary fibre and resistant starch that escaped digestion in the small intestine."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55329"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17319"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55329"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T21:21:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T21:26:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10009"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69873"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"h